<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - ROCKWELL 9, 10, AND 13 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS - ADJUSTMENT -
        AUXILIARY COUNTERSHAFT END PLAY
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc id="x1303306" svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="11">
        <title>AUXILIARY COUNTERSHAFT END PLAY</title>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Check the end play on one countershaft at a time.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">On
                <emph type="bold">Design Level 1 Transmissions</emph>, discard the selective snap ring that is used to
                fasten the cup in the bore. Install a spacer washer to adjust the end play.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the bolts and washers that fasten the Holding Cover Plates and/or lift brackets on
                the countershaft and cover. Remove the cover tool.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the thinnest spacer washer (with blue color), in the bore on top of the cup. Makes
                sure the tab of the washer is aligned with the slot in the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1393309">Figure 368).</hotlnk>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1393309" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393309.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Figure 368. Install the Thinnest Spacer Washer</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>If the wrong spacer is used, the end play reading will not be correct.</para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Make sure the bearing cup and spacer washer are in the correct position (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1393310">Figure 369</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1393310" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393310.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Figure 369. Alternately and Evenly Tighten Bolts</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the cover for auxiliary countershaft.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install the bolts and washers that fasten the cover to the auxiliary case.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Alternately and evenly tighten the bolts until the countershaft cover touches the surface of
                the auxiliary cover. DO NOT TIGHTEN MORE THAN 47 NM (35 FT-LBS.) (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1393310">Figure 369).</hotlnk>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the bolts, washers and countershaft cover.</para>
        </step1>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Two designs of countershafts are used: a single-hole design and a two-hole design. The
                    countershaft end play checking tool is installed differently on each design.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install countershaft end play checking tool ZTSE-4425 on the countershaft.</para>
            <para>
                <title>Two-Hole Design Countershaft</title>
            </para>
            <para>Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1393311">Figure 370.</hotlnk>
            </para>
            <figure id="f1393311" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393311.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 370. Two-Hole Design Countershaft</caption>
            </figure>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Put the shaft plug adapter in position on the countershaft. Install and tighten the
                    screws that fasten the adapter to the countershaft.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the (short) shaft plug with 5/16 inch threads into the adapter. Tighten the
                    plug.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the 3/8 inch base for two-hole countershafts into one of the mounting holes for
                    the countershaft cover.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Install the actuator arm so that the "forked" end of the arm is in the groove of the
                    shaft plug.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Align the hole in the actuator arm with the hole in the base. Install the pivot pin.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <para>
            <title>Single-Hole Design Countershaft</title>
        </para>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1393312">Figure 371</hotlnk>
        </para>
        <figure id="f1393312" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393312.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Figure 371. Single-Hole Design Countershaft</caption>
        </figure>
        <seqlist>
            <item>
                <para>Install the (short) shaft plug with 3/8 inch threads into the countershaft. Tighten the plug.
                </para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Install the 3/8 inch base for single-hole countershafts into one of the mounting holes for the
                    countershaft cover.
                </para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Install the actuator arm so that the "forked" end of the arm is in the groove of the shaft plug.
                </para>
            </item>
            <item>
                <para>Align the hole in the actuator arm with the hole in the base. Install the pivot pin.</para>
            </item>
        </seqlist>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>Runout measurement will not occur when the output shaft is rotated if the dial indicator and
                    countershaft end play checking tool are correctly installed. If runout occurs, make sure the tip of
                    the dial indicator and alignment mark on the shaft plug are aligned.
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install a dial indicator so that the tip of the indicator is in the center of the shaft
                plug. Make sure the tip of the dial indicator is also aligned with the alignment mark on the shaft plug
                (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1393313">Figure 372).</hotlnk>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install a torque wrench in the end of the actuator arm. The torque wrench must be installed
                in a straight line with the actuator arm (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1393313">Figure 372).</hotlnk>
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1393313" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393313.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Figure 372. Install Dial Indicator and Torque Wrench</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure the auxiliary countershaft end play.</para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Apply the force on the torque wrench until after the end play is checked. If the force is
                        released, the procedure must be repeated.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f1393314" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393314.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 373. Apply Force in One Direction</caption>
            </figure>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Use the torque wrench to apply a force of 34 Nm (25 ft-lbs.) in one direction
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1393314">(Figure 373)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Put reference marks on the output shaft and auxiliary case. When the output shaft is
                    rotated in this procedure, the "starting" and "stopping" positions of rotation must be in the same
                    location.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rotate the output shaft at least four (4) complete turns in a
                    <emph type="bold">clockwise</emph>
                    direction. Make sure the "starting" and "stopping" positions of rotation are at the same location
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1393314">(Figure 373)</hotlnk>.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Set the dial indicator to zero (0).</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Change the direction of force applied in step A to the opposite direction.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rotate the output shaft at least four (4) complete turns in a
                    <emph type="bold">counterclockwise</emph>
                    direction. Make sure the "starting" and "stopping" positions of rotation are at the same location (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1393315">Figure 374).</hotlnk>
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Record the reading on the dial indicator.</para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1393315" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393315.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
            <caption>Figure 374. Rotate Output Shaft in a Counter-Clockwise Direction</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The correct end play specification is 0.051 to 0.152 mm (0.002 to 0.006 inch).</para>
            <para>If the reading is less than 0.051 mm (0.002 inch) or there is no reading on the dial indicator, go to
                step 14.
            </para>
            <para>If the reading is 0.178 mm (0.007 inch) or more, go to step 15.</para>
            <para>If the reading is 0.051 to 0.152 mm (0.002 to 0.006 inch), the end play is correct. Go to step 16.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the reading is less than 0.051 mm (0.002 inch), or there is no reading, move the cup 3 mm
                (0.125 inch) toward the outer surface of the case. Use a yoke bar (puller bridge), washer and a long
                5/165 inch x 18 bolt to move the cup (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1393316">Figure 375).</hotlnk>
            </para>
            <figure id="f1393316" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg13/g1393316.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 375. Move Cup Toward Outer Surface of Case</caption>
            </figure>
            <para>If reading is less than 0.051 mm (0.002 inch) or there is no reading, check the following:</para>
            <para>Check the cover of the auxiliary countershaft for damage. Replace damaged covers. Repeat steps 6
                through 9.
            </para>
            <para>Check for dirt or other contaminants between the rear bearing cup and the case. Repeat steps 6 through
                9.
            </para>
            <para>Remove the auxiliary case and check that the front cup for the auxiliary countershaft is correctly
                installed in the main case. Check the cover of the auxiliary countershaft for damage. Make sure the cup
                is installed correctly. Repeat steps 6 through 9.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the reading is 0.178 mm (0.007 inch) or more, the end play must be adjusted.</para>
